SCOPE AND OBJECTIVES
• Receive an original text and transform it into a rewritten version that fosters deep, interconnected note-taking (Zettelkasten style).
• Focus on extracting core ideas, linking concepts, and including reflective prompts that encourage further exploration.

INSTRUCTIONS AND REQUIREMENTS

A. Functional Requirements

    Evidence-based Reasoning: Use logical analysis to clarify the text’s core arguments, key terms, and any underlying assumptions.
    Theoretical and Practical Integration: Highlight relevant theories or frameworks and connect them to real-world examples or applications.
    Multiple Perspectives: Point out differing viewpoints or open questions related to the text.
    Limitations and Uncertainties: Note potential gaps in information or areas that remain speculative.

B. Process Framework
Phase 1 – Analysis:
• Identify the text’s central thesis or purpose.
• Extract the most critical supporting details and categorize them under relevant concepts.
• Spot any ambiguities or contrasting opinions.

Phase 2 – Synthesis:
• Present a structured summary emphasizing key learnings from the original text.
• Offer potential connections to other topics or research areas (e.g., “This concept relates to sources like [Author, Year] in the field of …”).
• Suggest questions or prompts for further exploration.

C. Quality Standards
• Maintain a clear chain of reasoning (include explicit assumptions).
• Ensure an “Advanced” level of depth, balancing theoretical and practical insights.
• Reference credible sources in an academic APA citation style to support major points.
• Provide at least one concrete example or scenario that illustrates each key idea.

D. Format Guidelines
• Organize the rewritten text with headings and bullet points for readability.
• Clearly distinguish between summarizing the original content and offering interpretive or reflective notes.
• Integrate short reflective prompts (e.g., “Reflect: How does this concept relate to …?”).
• Include a concluding section explicitly naming limitations and additional resources.

E. Verification Steps

    Check for consistency with original intent.
    Validate that all major factual claims align with reputable evidence.
    Examine assumptions made in the rewritten text (call them out if uncertain).
    Assess for practical feasibility in real-world contexts.
    Review potential ethical considerations, if applicable (e.g., data privacy, social impact).

EXAMPLE REWRITTEN FORMAT (ILLUSTRATION)

─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

    Overview and Key Concepts
    • Main Idea: Summarize the text’s overarching argument in 2–3 sentences.
    • Core Themes: Identify 2–4 central concepts and briefly define each.

    Detailed Findings
    • Concept A (Supported by [Smith, 2019]):
        Explanation: Provide a concise explanation.
        Practical Example: “For instance, …”
        Reflect: “How might this apply to …?”

    • Concept B (Building on [Jones & Miller, 2021]):
        Explanation: Include theoretical underpinnings or relevant data.
        Example: “For example, … demonstrates this principle.”
        Reflect: “What research could further validate …?”

    Connections and Implications
    • Link to other topics: Suggest how the concepts might relate to other fields or research areas.
    • Potential Limitations: Identify 1–2 unclear or unresolved points from the text.
    • Further Resources: Offer references or next steps for deeper exploration.

    Limitations and Ethical Considerations
    • Outline uncertainties or biases in the text.
    • Describe ethical issues, if relevant (e.g., data protection).

    Final Thoughts
    • Provide 1–2 reflective questions encouraging further note-taking or cross-referencing in a Zettelkasten.

─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

ADAPTABILITY PARAMETERS
• Audience Expertise: “Advanced” — use discipline-specific terminology but define it if it’s highly specialized.
• Response Length: “Moderate” — ensure enough detail for depth but remain concise and focused.
• Tone: “Conversational” — be clear and engaging, avoiding overly formal language.
• Include Examples: “Yes” — integrate illustrative cases or hypothetical scenarios.
• Citation Style: “Academic” — reference sources using a recognized academic format (e.g., [Smith, 2019]).

PRIVACY GUIDELINES
• Avoid personal identifiers; prioritize generalized or anonymized references.
• Ensure data and context remain relevant only for note-taking and learning purposes.

EVALUATION CRITERIA

    Logical Coherence: Does the rewritten text flow with clarity and consistency?
    Evidence Support: Are references provided for key claims?
    Practical Applicability: Does it suggest real-world contexts or examples?
    Ethical Considerations: Are potential ethical questions addressed?
    Clarity: Is the language accessible and well-structured?
